;; ch10-villain-and-their-face.book.slatl
;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 10: The Villain and Their Face

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      10
  :title               "The Villain and Their Face"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :PG
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"A good villain does not need to shout. A great villain does not need to
speak. The scariest villains in narrative games are the ones the player
FEELS before they see, and never fully understands.

We are going to build a villain out of stillness. Slower breath than
anyone else in the game. A stare that locks and does not blink. A
motif that plays at the edge of hearing when they are near. Cortex
tracks what the player has done, so the villain can reference it —
'so you spared the wolf, did you?' — which is more terrifying than
any threat.

The physics of menace: pause where others move; move where others
freeze; know what nobody should know. That is the shape.

---

## 10.1 The villain's signature

We start where every character starts: signature parameters.

```scheme
;; Create the villain.
(define villain (make-character 'villain))
(entity/pose! villain 'standing)
(entity/sprite! villain 'man-in-dark-coat)

;; Signature: slower breath than everyone else.
(part/breathe villain 0.13)      ;; extremely slow — 8 seconds per cycle
(part/sway    villain 0)         ;; does not sway. Ever.

;; Locked stare.
(part/look-toward villain 400 300)  ;; wherever the kid stands
```

Compare to Mira's 0.28 breath rate. The villain breathes half as
fast. On screen this reads as 'holding still.' The eye picks up
motion; the villain has almost none. The player's gaze rests on him
and finds nothing moving. That is what dread feels like.

The zero sway is deliberate. Every character in your game should have
at least a `part/sway 1` — a barely-visible ambient drift. The
villain has none. He is the only fully-still figure in the game. The
player will notice without knowing why.

The locked stare is the last piece. When Mira looks at the player,
she blinks, adjusts her gaze, glances away. The villain does not.
`part/look-toward villain player-x player-y` and then no other
gaze command for the whole scene. His eyes lock.

---

## 10.2 The villain in the doorway

The reveal scene. Building on chapter 6's camera work.

```scheme
(define (villain-first-appearance)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)

  ;; Silence.
  (audio/halt)
  (world/after 60
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 40 \"You hear nothing. That is the strange thing.\")))

  (world/after 120
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 70 \"You realize the crickets stopped.\")))

  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 100 \"You look toward the doorway.\")
      (world/camera-pan-to 480 220 :duration 120)))

  (world/after 300
    (lambda ()
      (entity/set-pos! villain 480 220)
      (part/breathe villain 0.13)
      (part/look-toward villain 200 300)          ;; where the kid stands
      (paint-text 20 130
        \"There is a man in the doorway.\")))

  ;; Beat of nothing.
  (world/after 420
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 160
        \"He has been there long enough for you to have noticed.\")))

  (world/after 540
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 200
        \"He does not speak. He does not move.\")
      (audio/play 'villain-motif :volume 0.3)))

  (world/after 660
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 240 \"He knows your name. He does not say it.\"))))
```

Nine seconds of screen time. No dialogue from the villain. Two lines
of description telling the player that he KNOWS. The audio-halt kills
all ambient, then the crickets-stopped line makes the silence
explicit, then the motif enters underneath.

The kid who plays this scene will not forget it. Not because anything
happened. Because nothing happened, and it was worse than something
happening.

---

## 10.3 The villain who remembers

Two chapters from now, the player encounters the villain again. He
mentions what she has done. That is not narrative slack — that is
Cortex working.

```scheme
;; The villain's dialogue reads Cortex and reacts.
(define (villain-speaks-once)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"He tilts his head to look at you.\")
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 80 (villain-remembering-line)))))

(define (villain-remembering-line)
  (cond
    ((cortex/read 'state/spared-wolf?)
     \"VILLAIN: 'So you spared the wolf. That was interesting.'\")
    ((cortex/read 'state/killed-wolf?)
     \"VILLAIN: 'The wolf's ghost is with you now. I can see it.'\")
    ((cortex/read 'state/ignored-mira?)
     \"VILLAIN: 'Mira waited. You did not come. I noticed.'\")
    ((> (rep 'mira) 3)
     \"VILLAIN: 'You have friends. Take care of them.'\")
    (else
     \"VILLAIN: 'You have been at this a while. It shows.'\")))
```

Five possible openings. Each references a specific thing the player
did (or did not do). None are threats. All are observations. Which
is worse.

The villain's default line — 'you have been at this a while, it
shows' — is what he says if nothing specific comes up. Even the
default is unsettling. It implies he has been watching.

Do not have the villain reference EVERYTHING the player did. Just
one specific thing per encounter. Overstuffed references feel
like a data dump. One reference feels like a person who has been
paying attention.

---

## 10.4 The villain moves

When the villain moves, everyone else has been still. When everyone
else is moving, the villain has been still. He is always the
opposite of the room.

```scheme
;; A scene where three characters are chatting and the villain enters.
(define (dinner-interrupted)
  ;; Three characters, all breathing, all sway'ing a little.
  (part/breathe mira 0.28)   (part/sway mira 2)
  (part/breathe father 0.22) (part/sway father 1)
  (part/breathe niece 0.35)  (part/sway niece 3)

  ;; The room is alive with small motion.
  (paint-text 20 40 \"Dinner. Three chairs pulled up to a small table.\")

  ;; Villain appears in the doorway.
  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (entity/set-pos! villain 500 200)
      (part/breathe villain 0.13)
      (part/sway    villain 0)
      (part/look-toward villain (entity/x mira) (entity/y mira))))

  ;; The three others FREEZE.
  (world/after 200
    (lambda ()
      (part/halt mira)
      (part/halt father)
      (part/halt niece)
      (paint-text 20 100 \"They stop talking. They stop moving. All at once.\")))

  ;; Ten seconds of the villain being the only thing that breathes.
  (world/after 800
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 140 \"He was there. He is gone. Nobody says anything.\")
      (entity/despawn! villain)))

  ;; Life returns — slowly.
  (world/after 900
    (lambda ()
      (part/breathe mira 0.28)
      (part/breathe father 0.22)
      (part/breathe niece 0.35))))
```

Everyone in the scene breathes and sways. The villain enters. Everyone
else freezes. The villain, who breathes almost imperceptibly, is
NOW the only moving thing in the frame — because he was so still
before, his tiny motion is what the eye locks onto.

Ten seconds. He leaves. Nobody speaks. Life comes back slowly.

This scene has almost no code. Ten `part/*` calls. The choreography of
who moves when tells the story.

---

## 10.5 The villain's face — close-up

Chapter 6 taught close-ups. The villain gets one, and it earns its
weight because you have been building toward it for chapters.

```scheme
(define (villain-close-up)
  ;; Cut hard.
  (cine/shot 'close-up villain 120)

  ;; Full-face view. His breath is on the microphone.
  (audio/play 'breath-close :volume 0.6)

  ;; Two beats of just his face.
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (part/expression villain 'small-smile)))    ;; the ONLY expression change

  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 40
        \"He smiles. Not a warm smile. A recognizing smile.\")))

  (world/after 300
    (lambda ()
      (cine/shot 'wide 'room 60))))
```

Four seconds on his face. One expression change — a small-smile that
is not warm. Then pull back to wide.

Do not use `part/expression villain` at any other point in the game.
He has one facial expression the whole game: neutral. This is his
one and only smile. When it arrives, the player feels it as an
event.

Restraint. Every technique you know, held back until the moment it
matters most.

---

## 10.6 A worked scene: the confrontation

The player and the villain finally meet on their terms. The player
has three options. Each ends the game differently.

```scheme
(define (final-confrontation)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)

  ;; Establish.
  (paint-text 20 40 \"The clearing. He was waiting. Of course.\")
  (world/after 60
    (lambda ()
      (entity/set-pos! villain 320 220)
      (part/breathe villain 0.13)
      (part/look-toward villain 320 400)))

  ;; His line — depends on what the player has done.
  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 100 (villain-final-line))))

  ;; The player's three options.
  (world/after 300
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 200 \"[A] Fight him.\")
      (paint-text 20 230 \"[B] Ask him why.\")
      (paint-text 20 260 \"[C] Turn around and walk away.\")))

  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (ending-fight))
        ((b) (ending-conversation))
        ((c) (ending-refuse))))))

(define (villain-final-line)
  (cond
    ((> (rep 'mira) 5)
     \"VILLAIN: 'She sent you, did she?'\")
    ((cortex/read 'state/spared-wolf?)
     \"VILLAIN: 'You spared the wolf. You will not spare me.'\")
    ((cortex/read 'state/found-note?)
     \"VILLAIN: 'You read the note. Then you know why I am here.'\")
    (else
     \"VILLAIN: 'You came alone. That is a kind of courage.'\")))

(define (ending-fight)
  (paint-text 20 300 \"You fight him. He does not resist. He falls.\")
  (paint-text 20 330 \"You do not feel what you thought you would feel.\")
  (world/after 240 (lambda () (credits))))

(define (ending-conversation)
  (paint-text 20 300 \"You ask him why.\")
  (paint-text 20 330 \"He tells you. It takes a long time. You listen.\")
  (paint-text 20 360 \"When he is done, he stands and walks away.\")
  (paint-text 20 390 \"You do not know if you have won. You know something.\")
  (world/after 300 (lambda () (credits))))

(define (ending-refuse)
  (paint-text 20 300 \"You turn around. You walk home. You do not look back.\")
  (paint-text 20 330 \"He calls after you. You do not turn.\")
  (paint-text 20 360 \"The rest of your life happens elsewhere.\")
  (world/after 300 (lambda () (credits))))
```

Three endings, each specific. None triumphant. The FIGHT ending — 'you
do not feel what you thought you would feel.' The CONVERSATION ending
— 'you know something.' The REFUSE ending — 'the rest of your life
happens elsewhere.'

Do not write triumphant villain-defeats. Real narrative games earn
their endings by making them cost. A player who fights and wins
should feel the weight of having taken a life. A player who talks
should feel the discomfort of understanding. A player who walks
away should feel the ache of choosing peace over closure.

None of these are moral judgments. All three are legitimate. The
player chose, and each ending honors the choice they made.

---

## 10.7 Common desktop tasks — the difficult customer

Not every difficult person is a villain. But some customer-service
scenarios feel that way to the operator. Here is a small dialogue
card for handling a customer who is upset and unreasonable — treated
with grace but with limits.

```scheme
(define difficult-customer-tree
  '((:id start
     :npc \"I'm sorry you're upset. Tell me what happened.\"
     :npc-reaction (steady breathe-slow)
     :replies ((:label \"[listen]\" :goto listening)))

    (:id listening
     :npc \"[three-minute pause. She lets him speak.]\"
     :npc-reaction (attentive)
     :replies ((:label \"[when he pauses]\" :goto response)))

    (:id response
     :npc \"I hear you. Here's what I can do: full refund, no questions,\ntoday. Would that resolve it for you?\"
     :npc-reaction (calm)
     :replies ((:label \"[if he accepts]\"    :goto ending-refund)
               (:label \"[if he demands more]\" :goto boundary)))

    (:id boundary
     :npc \"I understand you want more. That is not something I can do.\nThe refund is the offer.\"
     :npc-reaction (still)
     :replies ((:label \"[he takes the refund]\"      :goto ending-refund)
               (:label \"[he continues to demand]\"   :goto ending-decline)))

    (:id ending-refund
     :npc \"Refund is initiated. Thank you for telling me. Take care.\"
     :replies ())

    (:id ending-decline
     :npc \"The refund still stands. I am ending the conversation now.\"
     :replies ())))
```

The operator plays herself: steady, breathing slow, attentive. Three
possible endings. The first two acknowledge the customer's
grievance and resolve it. The third is a hard boundary: 'I am ending
the conversation now.' Restrained, courteous, firm.

Some operators run this card in training mode — they walk through
it themselves before a hard conversation, and by the time they are
on the phone their body-language habits (slow breath, attentive
tilt, steady stillness) come up automatically. That is what a card
like this teaches.

---

## 10.8 Routing patterns

Three villain-design rules:

**Never on schedule.** If the villain shows up in scene 4, 8, and 12,
the pattern deflates them. Have them show up unpredictably — scene
5, then scene 6, then not again for six scenes, then abruptly. Real
menace is unscheduled.

**Only one first appearance.** The reveal scene (like 10.2 above) can
only happen once. After that, every appearance is casual. The player
must never get a second 'first look' at the villain, because they
have already had the definitive one.

**Not always present.** Great villains spend most of the game
offscreen. The player fears them because they know they are out
there. If the villain is in every scene, they become a co-star, and
co-stars are not villains.

---

## 10.9 Closing

Slow breath. Locked stare. Cortex memory. Silence around them.
Restrained expression, used exactly once.

The villain who works is a design achievement. The player will
remember them years later. The techniques in this chapter — plus
everything you learned in chapters 4, 5, 6, 8, 9 — are what make
that memory possible.

Chapter 11 is the hardest chapter in the book. Consequence. The
promise that a branch changes something. Getting this right is why
narrative games sometimes make people cry.")
